@node "SnoopRouter" "SnoopRouter"

@{MS "SnoopRouter"}

I use a little example to explain the usage of SnoopRouter. "SLAVE" is the hardware you want
to create an amiga driver for. "MASTER" is the system you that supports the "SLAVE"!@{par}

If your mobile is working with an PC, then "SLAVE" is your Handy and "MASTER" is your PC!@{par}

Connect SLAVE to your Amiga and use the same cable that is normaly used to connect it with the
MASTER! Now connect MASTER to your Amiga by using a null modem cable. This should look like
@{"this" link "/Data/Connect.ilbm/MAIN"}!@{par}

Now start SnoopRouter on Amiga by using the following template:

MASTERDEVICE=MD,MASTERUNIT=MU/N,MASTERBAUD=MB/N,SLAVEDEVICE=SD,SLAVEUNIT=SU/N,SLAVEBAUD=SB/N,DELAY/N,TO:@{par}

It look a bit komplex, but its easy to use. Its just the setup for two different serial devices for
Master and Slave! You must specify the ports MASTER and SLAVE are connected to. SnoopRouter virtualy
connects these ports, so you can control your SLAVE by using the MASTER like there are connected
direct. The only difference is that SnoopRouter is logging each transfered byte.@{par}

Examples:@{par}

SnoopRouter@{par}

Is opening the "serial.devive", unit 0 with 38400 baud as MASTER and the same device but unit 1 as
SLAVE! The logfile will written direct into the shell window.@{par}

SnoopRouter hyperCOM30Z.device to t:Camera.logfile@{par}

Here the device "hyperCOM30Z.device" unit 0 will be connected with the "hyperCOM30Z.device" unit 1!
Both sides are working with 38400! The logfile will be writen into "t:Camera.logfile"!@{par}

SnoopRouter hyperCOM30Z.device 0 57600 serial.device 0 38400@{par}

All data from HyperCOM (hyperCOM30Z.device, 57600 Baud, Unit 0) will be send by using the Amiga
internal serial port (serial.device, 38400 Baud, Unit 0) and vice versa! The logfile will be printed
on screen!@{par}

@endnode
@node "SnoopProtocol" "SnoopRouter - The Protocol"

@{MS "The Protocol"}

The protocol is very easy!@{par}

Each block begins with a direction index:@{par}

MAST - Master-Device sent data@{par}
SLAV - Slave-Device sent data@{par}
CONT - Continues last data message@{par}

Followed by a size ID and a four byte size indicator:@{par}

SIZExxxx@{par}

Now the data ID followed by 0x3A0A (":" and Linefeed) and xxxx bytes of data:@{par}

DATA(y*xxxx)@{par}

Take a look into the example: @{"DexDrive.log" link "/Data/DexDrive.log.hex/MAIN"} (Hex output done
with the AmigaDos type commmand)@{par}

@endnode

